WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.480
Congratulations! Our model's in production. The session is over. Now what do we do? Back

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:16.959
when we started this project, the goal was to build a model that provided some kind of

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:25.280
value for our company, for the public sector thing, for the world in general, and so we've

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:32.060
made a good start now that it's in production. Supposedly some enormous number of analytics

00:00:32.060 --> 00:00:39.200
projects never get off the ground at all, so okay, we're doing okay. But in practice,

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:44.240
deployment isn't actually the end of putting something into production, it's just the beginning,

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:50.480
it's the first gate. Really what we need to do is we need to be able to keep this in production

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:57.119
for an arbitrarily long amount of time in order for it to actually affect the changes

00:00:57.119 --> 00:01:04.000
that we want to happen. And typically, right, all of the stuff that happens after deployment

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.400
falls under the heading of model governance or something like this, which is, you know,

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:17.400
how do we keep this thing running when things change? Because a lot of stuff does change.

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:22.000
Companies are going to change out of under us. Sometimes production systems change. We

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.360
move from one system to another. Or maybe our model is amazing, and our business customer

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:34.680
wants us to change it. They want us to add new features or they want us to retrain for

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:39.000
some new use case or something like this. Anyway, we're going to have to retrain the

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.879
model, and so we're going to have to, like, work with it again in the future. Now, a lot

00:01:44.879 --> 00:01:48.440
of times when we talk about model governance, we think about the model object itself. We're

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:56.680
thinking about versioning, serving, monitoring for drift, these kinds of things. But in practice,

00:01:56.680 --> 00:02:03.120
a lot of what we actually end up doing involves sort of all the scaffolding around the model.

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:08.639
This is how the model is trained, how the model is validated. If we're responsible for

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:12.559
writing the code for inference, for working with predictions, there's a lot of code that

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:18.000
gets involved there, too. And so this talk is coming from experiences that I've had over

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.279
the last few years putting models into production, trying to keep them there, and sort of how

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:28.000
to think about model governance in this broader context, including all of the scaffolding

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.479
code. And so I want to center the talk on just this question, which is sort of what

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:37.399
can we do now while we're building the model, while we're designing how this is going to

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:45.240
work to make our maintenance job easier later? And in practice, you know, there's I think

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:50.839
we can distill it down to a few core practices that can really help with this. Core principles

00:02:50.839 --> 00:02:56.679
that serve as a foundation for this. Let's see if you're ready for this list. These are

00:02:56.679 --> 00:03:06.600
things like packaging, documentation, testing, writing legible code. Take it in. I know what

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:14.160
you're thinking. Wow. This is going to change my life. No one has ever told me before that

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:20.520
I should document my code. But the trick here is that in the governance context, these go

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:26.800
from nice things that we should do, maybe, to things that sort of all stack on top of

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:34.960
each other in order to produce a model or a model system that then we can maintain over

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:39.440
time and can keep providing that value, even as we have to retrain it, we have to adapt

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:45.600
it, we have to change it, right? And this talk is about R. This is the context in which

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:50.399
I was working on the project that inspired this talk. But a lot of this stuff is just

00:03:50.399 --> 00:03:56.520
as applicable to Python as anything else. So, you know, I'd love to talk after I write

00:03:56.520 --> 00:04:01.119
a ton of Python code, I write a ton of R code, would be happy to talk about ways that this

00:04:01.119 --> 00:04:05.440
applies in Python the same way it does in R. It's just all the examples and stuff are

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:12.839
going to be in R. So let's start with packaging. And I start here because this is foundational

00:04:12.839 --> 00:04:18.279
to everything else. And to be clear, I don't mean packaging like we're going to release

00:04:18.279 --> 00:04:25.279
this on CRAN. Most of what I do is proprietary. I work in consulting. So I work with a client.

00:04:25.279 --> 00:04:29.519
It stays in their environment. It stays in their version control, right? We're not putting

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:36.160
this anywhere. But packaging is still tremendously useful because this provides a structure to

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:42.399
support things like automation and lots of the other sort of governance and maintenance

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:48.980
details. I try to do this with almost every analytics project I do of reasonable complexity

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:55.200
for this reason. And it does a couple of things. First, packages provide structure. Literally

00:04:55.200 --> 00:05:01.440
they provide a file structure. Our metadata goes here. Our R files go here. Our tests

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:05.880
go here. Our documentation goes here. This at the very least helps to avoid the thing

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:12.880
that you'll get in teams, in academia, like where I've come from, where you have scripts

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:17.920
just kind of everywhere in a folder, and this is our production model. Like this helps avoid

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:24.119
this, right? But also it does a lot of other things. It structures your dependencies. So

00:05:24.119 --> 00:05:28.760
if your model depends on other packages, it helps declare and maintain those kinds

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:35.559
of things. So as the world changes, we can redeploy, rebuild with some amount of confidence.

00:05:35.559 --> 00:05:41.920
The other thing it tracks is things like your code version, right? And this is important

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:47.160
in at least two cases in governance. One is I don't just want to know the model version

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:51.440
that we're running. I would really like to know what version of my code base trained

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:57.239
that model, right? Or if I'm responsible for inference, like I am in the project I

00:05:57.239 --> 00:06:01.720
was referring to, I also want to be able to capture what version of the inference code

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:05.399
was used. There are other ways you can do this, but this just puts the number in one

00:06:05.399 --> 00:06:11.119
place and it propagates throughout, right? As you use your package. So it provides a

00:06:11.119 --> 00:06:13.920
structure. The other thing it does is it supports a bunch

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:20.440
of useful automations using other really cool packages you've maybe used before, like DevTools.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:26.679
This supports things like auto-generating package documentation by just calling document.

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:32.600
Or running all of your tests in a package using test. It also supports some more holistic

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:36.279
kinds of things, like with the check, which runs our command check and a whole bunch of

00:06:36.279 --> 00:06:42.359
other stuff that will basically test that your package is loadable and usable by all

00:06:42.359 --> 00:06:48.119
of your potential downstream users. And you can bundle this into something like continuous

00:06:48.119 --> 00:06:52.079
integration, you know, a GitHub workflow or something. So every time I make any meaningful

00:06:52.079 --> 00:06:56.279
change to my package, this all happens automatically. People don't have to think about it, which

00:06:56.279 --> 00:06:59.359
is sort of the point. I want to be thinking about the code. I don't want to be thinking

00:06:59.359 --> 00:07:03.119
about all of this other kind of governance stuff. I don't have to.

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:07.799
And then finally, this builds on typical R patterns. This is what any R user would expect.

00:07:07.799 --> 00:07:13.279
Is instead of having to write some kind of proprietary, you know, thing where we're sourcing

00:07:13.279 --> 00:07:17.880
a bunch of files or making sure they're in the right order, right? We can just call library

00:07:18.359 --> 00:07:24.920
for our little fictional package here, classifier, and then we can just use functions, right?

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:29.079
We've built this into a package structure, so any R user, whether it's next month, next

00:07:29.079 --> 00:07:33.959
year or in two years, can use this code base the way that we would expect, right?

00:07:33.959 --> 00:07:38.359
So this starts as a foundation, and then we can build on it with things like documentation.

00:07:38.359 --> 00:07:41.880
This is probably the least surprising part of this framework, so I won't spend too much

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:48.880
time on this, but it's super helpful, because it works at multiple timescales.

00:07:48.880 --> 00:07:57.399
In the governance context, documentation helps to provide us sort of contract for how things

00:07:57.399 --> 00:08:04.480
work. It starts by helping future you or whoever's going to be maintaining your package, because

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:08.559
in a lot of cases, it probably will be you, but it's going to be you in six months or

00:08:08.559 --> 00:08:13.320
12 months when you don't have all the context loaded up that you do right now about the

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:19.200
problem, the domain, the sort of stakeholders, the weird sort of conflicting things you've

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:22.839
got to take account of. The other thing it helps you do is it helps

00:08:22.839 --> 00:08:28.559
you right now, because it sort of helps get you away from sort of vibes-based programming

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:33.679
and gets you into something more resembling a contract. If in at least the most basic

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:39.640
form I can write down, what should this function do? What does it take in, and what does it

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:44.479
take out? I've sort of forced myself to think about that, and so this is going to help you

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:50.919
later in the governance process. The other thing is, like, in this ecosystem

00:08:50.919 --> 00:08:56.599
that we're all sort of swimming in, documentation offers a lot of other really nice functionality,

00:08:56.599 --> 00:09:01.840
right? If you're working in Positron or you're working in RStudio, if you write help, even

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:08.559
really basic help, you don't have to go crazy, you get nice help integrated into your IDE.

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:14.080
You get auto-completion, even if you're doing pipes and this kind of thing. Again, all you

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:19.880
have to do is document your arguments. You don't have to write a treatise. Plus, in the

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:25.679
world we're in now, all of this documentation can get sucked up by language models or sort

00:09:25.679 --> 00:09:30.559
of other things, too, to power sort of other experiences.

00:09:30.559 --> 00:09:34.359
And so it's not just something that's like, oh, we should do this, you know? We get real

00:09:34.359 --> 00:09:41.400
benefits from this, both now and sort of downstream. And then there's testing, which for a long

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:46.200
time for me was kind of something that's, I should do this. I don't really know how

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:53.400
to get started. I'm not a software developer. I didn't go to school for computer science.

00:09:53.400 --> 00:10:00.679
But it is really, really useful, and it's really important in this context. Because

00:10:00.679 --> 00:10:06.039
testing is what's going to provide us with some kind of a safety harness once our model

00:10:06.039 --> 00:10:12.599
is in production and we need to then change it. Because, I don't know, code's complicated,

00:10:12.599 --> 00:10:19.400
and we can make mistakes, and I want something that's going to catch me if I make a mistake.

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:28.280
Yes, I want to cancel this update. So and this helps us answer a couple of questions

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:34.280
in particular. One, does my code work right now? Right? So if you� again, this is sort

00:10:34.280 --> 00:10:40.179
of moving away from vibes-based coding, where instead of saying, yeah, this model seems

00:10:40.179 --> 00:10:44.599
to do what I want, or, yes, this transformation function seems to do what I want, it lets

00:10:44.599 --> 00:10:51.200
us write something down in code that can ensure that. But then more importantly, later,

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:56.400
when you can't remember how this stuff worked, this helps me know, does my code still work?

00:10:56.400 --> 00:11:00.919
And this is particularly important when you start having a larger code base for, like,

00:11:00.919 --> 00:11:07.559
a model or model functions that have lasted a while, and changes in part A are going to

00:11:07.559 --> 00:11:14.239
affect part, you know, F over here. And you can't keep that all in your head.

00:11:14.239 --> 00:11:18.080
There's also all kinds of interesting stuff where you start depending on other packages,

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:23.200
and packages change and update over time, right? Maybe you didn't do anything, but maybe

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:30.119
a dependency broke something. Or maybe I did. That happens. Tests catch you for this kind

00:11:30.119 --> 00:11:35.559
of thing. The good news is it's getting easier and easier,

00:11:35.559 --> 00:11:42.719
I think, to start growing in this capacity. It's, you know, what do we do? I mean, there's

00:11:42.719 --> 00:11:46.880
ways to start small and grow from there, right? We don't have to boil the ocean to

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:51.799
do testing. We have a lot of tools that help with this now.

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:55.760
And what you can do to get started and what we've done on some of our key projects are

00:11:55.760 --> 00:12:03.520
really just two steps. One, identify and test your key functionality. In a modeling context,

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:09.960
this might be a main training function using little bits of, you know, reproducible data.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:15.080
This might be inference functionality. Or it might be, like, complicated transformation

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:20.239
stuff where you have to smash data frames together. And any time you do that, you can

00:12:20.239 --> 00:12:26.760
have missing values, misjoins, right? If you're using untrusted data, you can have a bad time.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:30.599
And so this lets you sort of test the things you think are most likely to go wrong. So

00:12:30.599 --> 00:12:33.140
you can do a couple of those. You don't have to do a lot.

00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:40.179
But then over time, as we add new work or as we fix bugs, because they happen, we can

00:12:40.179 --> 00:12:44.299
just write a test that says, oh, can I catch this bug, right? Can I figure out where the

00:12:44.299 --> 00:12:48.460
bug is? Can I test it? And then fix the bug. And so now the bug will never happen to you

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:54.299
again, at least not without you knowing it. And we have lots of really good tools for

00:12:54.299 --> 00:12:59.380
this now. Packages like test that, which I think in version 3 is when they introduced

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:05.059
snapshots, which makes it super easy to write tests. And basically it works in a three-part

00:13:05.059 --> 00:13:10.500
model. You start with some known data. So, like, the iris data set here in this example.

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:17.219
This is not random data. Like, it's deterministic. We know what these data are. Capture the output.

00:13:17.219 --> 00:13:23.020
And then call this function expect snapshot with your output. On the first run, what this

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:26.820
is going to do is write a little markdown file into your package structure that stores

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:32.500
things like what the call was, any output messages, and the actual output of the object.

00:13:32.500 --> 00:13:38.179
And it just writes it to a little markdown file. The next time that you call this, it's

00:13:38.179 --> 00:13:42.500
just going to go read that file, and it's going to figure out whether or not it's reproducible.

00:13:42.500 --> 00:13:47.380
I didn't have to write any super fancy, you know, test conditions or anything like that.

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:50.820
As a way to get started, this is pretty good. It also helps you sort of ensure that your

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:57.820
code is deterministic. If you get, you know, it will yell at you if it's not.

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:02.419
And then finally, sort of the layer on top would be writing legible code. Right? We've

00:14:02.419 --> 00:14:08.099
got packaging. We've got docs and tests. But then if we want people to be able to use our

00:14:08.099 --> 00:14:12.539
code into the future, this is where writing legible code I think really helps. Because

00:14:12.539 --> 00:14:18.780
the real world is more complicated than demos. We have data that are complicated and involve

00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:24.539
lots of merging. We have models that aren't just one little model object we trained. It's

00:14:24.539 --> 00:14:29.500
multiple model objects that have to be managed together and maybe interact. In our project

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:34.820
before, we had a two-stage model where one flowed into the other. Both were trainable.

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:40.820
There can also be complicated prediction logic if you have to manage state for multiple models.

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:44.380
One approach to do this would be, you know, and it's fine, would be to just bundle everything

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:49.900
together in lists. Right? I train my model and out the end of it comes a list with two

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:54.739
parts. A preparatory thing and a model thing. So we get that. And then, you know, if we

00:14:54.739 --> 00:15:00.460
want to do inference, maybe we extract the different parts of the model and we call some

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:06.239
function that uses all these different pieces together. Right? You can do that, but we already

00:15:06.239 --> 00:15:12.940
have a nicer way to do this in R using S3 objects and S3 methods. If you use R, you're

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:18.780
used to calling print on something and getting a nice output. If you call predict, you get

00:15:18.780 --> 00:15:23.840
a nice output. The good news is getting this kind of thing is really, really easy and adopting

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:31.859
it has made life better for me and for us. You can do this in two easy steps. First,

00:15:31.859 --> 00:15:36.580
instead of returning a list, here's our original list that we had before. Return a list just

00:15:36.580 --> 00:15:41.940
with one extra attribute attached called class. Call it anything you want. I called it classifier

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:47.140
model because it matches the package. Once you have that, you can write this funny named

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:53.099
function. Predict.classifier model. And then just put whatever complex nonsense that you

00:15:53.099 --> 00:15:58.700
want to go in there. But once you do that, your users can just use predict from now on.

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:02.419
They don't have to know what's going on. You can abstract it all away, which hopefully

00:16:02.419 --> 00:16:06.539
you were going to do anyway. But now they can just behave� they can work in the R

00:16:06.539 --> 00:16:11.539
ecosystem the way that they should be used to doing anyway. This is good for downstream.

00:16:11.539 --> 00:16:17.479
This is particularly good if you're responsible for inference. Like in this project, we were

00:16:17.479 --> 00:16:23.340
responsible for maintaining the R stub files that actually did inference and then were

00:16:23.340 --> 00:16:31.299
orchestrated by the DevOps team. And so this lets us make our stub files be expressive

00:16:31.299 --> 00:16:35.900
and easy to understand and self-contained. They just call the package and they do the

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:40.419
thing. You can also extend this to other methods, too, if you want. You want to define something

00:16:40.419 --> 00:16:44.419
entirely new. I found out this was actually defined in generics the other day, but we're

00:16:44.419 --> 00:16:50.780
going to pretend that we invented it. You define it using use method. Literally, this

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:54.219
is not even like� this is not even like toy code. You just write this. This is all

00:16:54.219 --> 00:16:59.580
you have to do. And then you can define your S3 method this way. And again, now I have

00:16:59.580 --> 00:17:04.859
this function explain that I can call on my object, right? You can define things very

00:17:04.859 --> 00:17:09.939
easily so then when people come back to your code later, it's more expressive, it follows

00:17:09.939 --> 00:17:16.859
the conventions of the ecosystem. And so even though none of these things are

00:17:16.859 --> 00:17:23.780
probably like mind-blowing new things, what we have found is that when we combine these

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:30.660
kinds of principles together, it has made our model more maintainable over time. This

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:36.380
particular case, we've been in production for a few years now for a client. It's made

00:17:36.380 --> 00:17:42.680
a ton of value for them. And we've even survived a transition from, like, an air flow-based

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:47.459
architecture to, like, Databricks comes in and sells them all the things. So now we're

00:17:47.459 --> 00:17:53.739
in Databricks. We were able to lift this, move it over, in part because of this kind

00:17:53.739 --> 00:17:59.180
of an infrastructure. So I would love to talk more about this later. I would love to hear

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:06.380
ways that you do this, you do other things. Yeah. I appreciate you letting me be here.

